son, James I., Jr.]] ''Stonewall Jackson: The Man, The Soldier, The Legend''. New York: Macmillan Publishing, 1997. {{ISBN|0-02-864685-1}}.\n* [[Stephen W. Sears|Sears, Stephen W.]] ''Gettysburg''. Boston: Houghton Mifflin, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0-395-86761-7}}.\n* [[Jeff Sharlet (writer)|Sharlet, Jeff]]. \"Through a Glass, Darkly: How the Christian Right is Reimagining U.S. History.\" ''Harpers'', December 2006.\n* Taylor, Richard. [http://docsouth.unc.edu/fpn/taylor/menu.html ''Destruction and Reconstruction: Personal Experiences of the Late War'']. Nashville, Tennessee: J.S. Sanders & Co., 2001. {{ISBN|1-879941-21-X}}. First published 1879 by D. Appleton.\n* [[Trudeau, Noah Andre]]. ''Gettysburg: A Testing of Courage''. New York: HarperCollins, 2002. {{ISBN|978-0-06-019363-8}}.\n* [[Jeffry D. Wert|Wert, Jeffry D.]] ''General James Longstreet: The Confederacy's Most Controversial Soldier: A Biography''. New York: Simon & Schuster, 1993. {{ISBN|978-0-671-70921-1}}.\n* [http://www.vmi.edu/archives2.aspx?id=5005 Jackson genealogy site] at [[Virginia Military Institute]]\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n<!-- * {{cite book|author=|title=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|url=}} -->\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Austin|first1=Aurelia|title=Georgia boys with \"Stonewall\" Jackson: James Thomas Thompson and the Walton Infantry|date=1967|publisher=University of Georgia Press|location=Athens|isbn=9780820335230|url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/ugapressbks/do-pdf:ugp9780820335230|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}\n* Chambers, Lenoir. ''Stonewall Jackson''. New York: Morrow, 1959. {{OCLC|186539122}}.\n* [[John Esten Cooke|Cooke, John Esten]], Moses Drury Hoge, and John William Jones. [https://books.google.com/books?id=DKHFaHBX2isC ''Stonewall Jackson: A Military Biography'']. New York: D. Appleton and Company, 1876. {{OCLC|299589}}.\n* Cozzens, Peter. ''Shenandoah 1862: Stonewall Jackson's Valley Campaign''. Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-8078-3200-4}}.\n* [[Robert Lewis Dabney|Dabney, R. L.]] [https://books.google.com/books?id=-G0FAAAAQAAJ ''Life of Lieut.-Gen. Thomas J. Jackson (Stonewall Jackson)'']. London: James Nisbet and Co., 1866. {{OCLC|457442354}}.\n* Douglas, Henry Kyd. ''I Rode with Stonewall: The War Experiences of the Youngest Member of Jackson's Staff''. Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 1940. {{ISBN|0-8078-0337-5}}.\n* [[S. C. Gwynne|Gwynne, S. C.]] ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=h_-YBAAAQBAJ Rebel Yell: The Violence, Passion, and Redemption of Stonewall Jackson]''. New York: [[Simon & Schuster]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-4516-7328-9}}.\n*[[Benjamin King (author)|King, Benjamin]]. ''A Bullet for Stonewall'', Pelican Publishing Company, 1990,. {{ISBN|0882897683}}.\n* Lively, Mathew W. ''Calamity at Chancellorsville: The Wounding and Death of Confederate General Stonewall Jackson''. El Dorado Hills, California: Savas Beatie, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-61121-138-2}}.\n* Mackowski, Chris, and Kristopher D. White. ''The Last Days of Stonewall Jackson: The Mortal Wounding of the Confederacy's Greatest Icon''. El Dorado Hills, California: Savas Beatie, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1-61121-150-4}}.\n* Robertson, James I., Jr. ''Stonewall Jackson's Book of Maxims''. Nashville, Tennessee: Cumberland House, 2002. {{ISBN|1-58182-296-0}}.\n* Shackel, Paul A. ''Archaeology and Created Memory: Public History in a National Park''. New York: Kluwer Academic/Plenum Publishers, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-306-46177-4}}.\n* White, Henry A. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ErA-AAAAYAAJ ''Stonewall Jackson'']. Philadelphia: G.W. Jacobs and Co., 1909. {{OCLC|3911913}}.\n* Wilkins, J. Steven. ''All Things for Good: The Steadfast Fidelity of Stonewall Jackson''. Nashville, Tennessee: Cumberland House Publishing, 2004. {{ISBN|1-58182-225-1}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Stonewall Jackson}}\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Jackson, Thomas Jonathan}}\n{{wikisourcepar|Stonewall Jackson's Last Battle}}\n* [http://www.vmi.edu/archives.aspx?id=3747 Virginia Military Institute Archives Stonewall Jackson Resources]\n* [http://www.shapell.org/manuscript.aspx?stonewall-jackson-shortly before-death-on-maryland Stonewall Jackson Original Letter as Lieutenant General, Near Fredericksburg, 1863] Shapell Manuscript Foundation\n* [http://thomaslegion.net/generalstonewalljacksongenealogy.html Jackson genealogy site]\n* [http://atlnewspapers.galileo.usg.edu/atlnewspapers/view?docId=news/asc1863/asc1863-0305.xml&query=stonewall%20jackson%20dead&brand=atlnewspapers-brand  \"Death of 'Stonewall' Jackson], Southern Confederacy, May 12, 1863. [http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/atlnewspapers/ Atlanta Historic Newspapers Archive]. Digital Library of Georgia.\n* {{Find a Grave|536}}\n* {{Find a Grave|2739}}\n* [http://www.civilwarhome.com/fleechancellorsville.htm Fitzhugh Lee's 1879 address on Chancellorsville]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060613064119/http://stonewalljackson.org/ The Stonewall Jackson House]\n* [http://www.civilwaranimated.com/index.php/stonewall-jackson Animated history of the campaigns of Stonewall Jackson]\n* [http://www.oldbaileyonline.org/browse.jsp?id=t17490113-2-defend40&div=t17490113-2#highlight Details on John Jackson's larceny trial in the Court Records of the Old Bailey]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130828223652/http://www.winchesterhistory.org/stonewall_jackson.htm] Stonewall Jackson's Headquarters, Winchester VA\n* [http://www.civilwarfieldtrips.com/chancellorsville/guineastation.htm] Guinea Station, the place where Thomas Jackson died\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=''(none)''}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander of the Stonewall Brigade]]|years=April 27, 1861 \u2013 October 28, 1861}} \n{{s-aft|after=[[Richard B. Garnett]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Virginia Military Institute}}\n{{Stonewall}}\n{{Stonewall Brigade}}\n{{Frederick County, Virginia in the American Civil War}}\n{{American Civil War|Leaders}}\n{{Hall of Fame for Great Americans}}\n{{Authority contro